The etymology of the word "foid" ("foo-id") tracks to young Dr. Raymond Peat's favorite 1930s comic "Smokey Stover" and its prominent use of nonsense word "foo", peppering puns off it  ("foo fighter", "foomobile", "foosic", "foo-d", "where there's foo, there's fire") in his work.

"Foo" ultimately comes from the Chinese "fu" character for good fortune (which women often bring) per its own author. The attentive reader will also note "foo" is where the "foo fighters" term for the Axis UFOs that Allied soldiers spotted (German Patent Office) also originated.

NB: You must be faithful to the foid for the fortune to persist. Check Miguel Serrano's thoughts on Napoleon and Josephine. He was also a foo fighter truther funnily enough. This shows romantic fidelity's importance being not merely moral, but also of a higher metaphysical order.
